# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barquentine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The **17th century** lasted from January 1, 1601 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCI), to December 31, 1700 (MDCC).
[src:barquentine/17th-century] From the mid-17th century, European politics were increasingly dominated by the Kingdom of France of Louis XIV, where royal power was solidified domestically in the civil war of the Fronde.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The semi-feudal territorial French nobility was weakened and subjugated to the power of an absolute monarchy through the reinvention of the Palace of Versailles from a hunting lodge to a gilded prison, in which a greatly expanded royal court could be more easily kept under surveillance.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] With domestic peace assured, Louis XIV caused the borders of France to be expanded.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] It was during this century that the English monarch became increasingly involved in conflicts with the Parliament, which would culminate in the English civil war and an end to the dominance of the English monarchy.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] It was also a period of development of culture in general (especially theater, music, visual arts and philosophy).
[src:barquentine/17th-century] Some of the greatest inventions took place in this century.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] It was during this period that the European colonization of the Americas began in earnest, including the exploitation of the silver deposits, which resulted in bouts of inflation as wealth was drawn into Europe.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] Also during this period, there would be a more intense European presence in Southeast Asia and East Asia (such as the colonization of Taiwan).
[src:barquentine/17th-century] These foreign elements would contribute to a revolution in Ayutthaya.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The Mataram Sultanate and the Aceh Sultanate would be the major powers of the region, especially during the first half of the century.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] In the Islamic world, the gunpowder empires – the Ottoman, Safavid, and Mughal – grew in strength as well.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The southern half of India would see the decline of the Deccan Sultanates and extinction of the Vijayanagara Empire.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The Dutch would colonize Ceylon and endure hostilities with Kandy.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The end of the 17th century saw the first major surrender of Ottoman territory in Europe when the Treaty of Karlowitz ceded most of Hungary to the Habsburgs in 1699.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] In Japan, Tokugawa Ieyasu established the Tokugawa shogunate at the beginning of the century, beginning the Edo period; the isolationist Sakoku policy began in the 1630s and lasted until the 19th century.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] In China, the collapsing Ming dynasty was challenged by a series of conquests led by the Manchu warlord Nurhaci, which were consolidated by his son Hong Taiji and finally consummated by his grandson, the Shunzhi Emperor, founder of the Qing dynasty.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] Qing China spent decades of this century with economic problems (results of civil wars between the Qing and former Ming dynasty loyalists), only recovering well at the end of the century.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] The greatest military conflicts of the century were the Thirty Years' War, Dutch–Portuguese War, the Great Turkish War, the Nine Years' War, Mughal–Safavid Wars, and the Qing annexation of the Ming.
[src:barquentine/17th-century] Major changes in philosophy and science take place, often characterized as the Scientific Revolution.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:barquentine/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:barquentine/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Well-known ancient artwork and sculptures, each representing a certain civilisation.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] The three-age system periodises ancient history into the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age, with recorded history usually considered to begin with the Bronze Age.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] The start and end of the three ages vary between world regions.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] In many regions the Bronze Age is generally considered to begin a few centuries prior to 3000 BC, while the end of the Iron Age varies from the early first millennium BC in some regions to the late first millennium AD in others.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] During the time period of ancient history, the world population was exponentially increasing due to the Neolithic Revolution, which was in full progress.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] In 10,000 BC, the world population stood at an estimated 2 million, it rose to 45 million by 3000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] By the Iron Age in 1000 BC, the population had risen to 72 million.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] By the end of the ancient period in AD 500, the world population is thought to have stood at 209 million.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] In 10,500 years, the world population increased by 100 times.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Prehistory is the period before written history.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Most of the knowledge of that period comes from the work of archaeologists.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] The early human migrations in the Lower Paleolithic saw *Homo erectus* spread across Eurasia 1.8 million years ago.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for the use of fire has been dated as early as 1.8 million years ago, a date which is contested, with generally accepted evidence for the controlled use of fire dating to 780,000 years ago.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Actual use of hearths first appears 400,000 years ago.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Dates for the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (modern humans) range from 250,000 to 160,000 years ago, with the varying dates being based on DNA studies and fossils respectively.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Some 50,000 years ago, *Homo sapiens* migrated out of Africa.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] They reached Australia about 45,000 years ago, southwestern Europe about the same time, southeastern Europe and Siberia around 40,000 years ago, and Japan about 30,000 years ago.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Humans migrated to the Americas about 15,000 years ago.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for agriculture emerges in about 9000 BC in what is now eastern Turkey and spread through the Fertile Crescent.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Settlement at Göbekli Tepe began around 9500 BC and may have the world's oldest temple.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] The Nile River Valley has evidence of sorghum and millet cultivation starting around 8000 BC and agricultural use of yams in Western Africa perhaps dates to the same time period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Cultivation of millet, rice, and legumes began around 7000 BC in China.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Taro cultivation in New Guinea dates to about 7000 BC also with squash cultivation in Mesoamerica perhaps sharing that date.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Animal domestication began with the domestication of dogs, which dates to at least 15,000 years ago, and perhaps even earlier.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Sheep and goats were domesticated around 9000 BC in the Fertile Crescent, alongside the first evidence for agriculture.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Other animals, such as pigs and poultry, were later domesticated and used as food sources.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Cattle and water buffalo were domesticated around 7000 BC and horses, donkeys, and camels were domesticated by about 4000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] All of these animals were used not only for food, but to carry and pull people and loads, greatly increasing human ability to do work.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] The invention of the simple plough by 6000 BC further increased agricultural efficiency.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Metal use in the form of hammered copper items predates the discovery of smelting of copper ores, which happened around 6000 BC in western Asia and independently in eastern Asia before 2000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Gold and silver use dates to between 6000 and 5000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Alloy metallurgy began with bronze in about 3500 BC in Mesopotamia and was developed independently in China by 2000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Pottery developed independently throughout the world, with fired pots appearing first among the Jomon of Japan and in West Africa at Mali.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Sometime between 5000 and 4000 BC the potter's wheel was invented.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] By 3000 BC, the pottery wheel was adapted into wheeled vehicles which could be used to carry loads further and easier than with human or animal power alone.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Writing developed separately in five different locations in human history: Mesopotamia, Egypt, India, China, and Mesoamerica.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] By 3400 BC, "proto-literate" cuneiform spread in the Middle East.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Egypt developed its own system of hieroglyphs by about 3200 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] By 2800 BC the Indus Valley Civilisation had developed its Indus script, which remains undeciphered.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Chinese Characters were independently developed in China during the Shang dynasty in the form of the Oracle Bone Script dating to the period 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p01] Writing in Mesoamerica dates to 600 BC with the Zapotec civilization.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The ancient Near East is considered the cradle of civilisation.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It began the study of the stars and the sciences of astronomy and mathematics.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Mesopotamia is the site of some of the earliest known civilisations in the world.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural communities emerged in the area with the Halaf culture around 8000 BC and continued to expand through the Ubaid period around 6000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Cities began in the Uruk period (4000–3100 BC) and expanded during the Jemdet Nasr (3100–2900 BC) and Early Dynastic (2900–2350 BC) periods.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The surplus of storable foodstuffs created by this economy allowed the population to settle in one place instead of migrating after crops and herds.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It also allowed for a much greater population density, and in turn required an extensive labour force and division of labour.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This organisation led to the necessity of record keeping and the development of writing.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia was an Amorite state in lower Mesopotamia (modern southern Iraq), with Babylon as its capital.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia emerged when Hammurabi created an empire out of the territories of the former kingdoms of Sumer and Akkad.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire, or Chaldea, was Babylonia from the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Under the reign of Nebuchadnezzar II, it conquered Jerusalem.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This empire also created the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the still-surviving Ishtar Gate as architectural embellishments of its capital at Babylon.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Akkad was a city and its surrounding region near Babylon.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Akkad also became the capital of the Akkadian Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Despite an extensive search, the precise site has never been found.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Akkad reached the height of its power between about 2330 and 2150 BC, following the conquests of King Sargon of Akkad.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Through the spread of Sargon's empire, the language of Akkad, known as Akkadian from the city, spread and replaced the Sumerian language in Mesopotamia and eventually by 1450 BC was the main language of diplomacy in the Near East.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Assyria was originally a region on the Upper Tigris, where a small state was created in the 19th century BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The capital was at Assur, which gave the state its name.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Later, as a nation and empire that came to control all of the Fertile Crescent, Egypt, and much of Anatolia, the term "Assyria proper" referred to roughly the northern half of Mesopotamia (the southern half being Babylonia), with Nineveh as its capital.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Assyrian kings controlled a large kingdom at three different times in history.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These are called the *Old* (20th to 18th centuries BC), *Middle* (14th to 11th centuries BC), and *Neo-Assyrian* (9th to 7th centuries BC) kingdoms, or periods.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Mitanni was a Hurrian empire in northern Mesopotamia founded around 1500 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Mitanians conquered and controlled Assyria until the 14th century BC while contending with Egypt for control of parts of modern Syria.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Its capital was Washukanni, whose precise location has not been determined by archaeologists.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Medes and Persians were peoples who had appeared in the Iranian plateau around 1500 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Both peoples spoke Indo-European languages and were mostly pastoralists with a tradition of horse archery.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Medes established their own Median Empire by the 6th century BC, having defeated the Neo-Assyrian Empire with the Chaldeans in 614 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid Empire was founded by Cyrus the Great, who first became king of the Persians, then conquered the Medes, Lydia, and Babylon by 539 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The empire built on earlier Mesopotamian systems of government to govern their large empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By building roads, they improved both the ability to send governmental instructions throughout their lands as well as improving the ability of their military forces to be deployed rapidly.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Increased trade and upgraded farming techniques increased wealth, but also exacerbated inequalities between social classes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The empire's location at the centre of trading networks spread its intellectual and philosophical ideas throughout a wide area, and its religion, while not itself spreading far, had an impact on later religions such as Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Cyrus' son Cambyses II conquered Egypt, while a later emperor, Darius the Great, expanded the empire to the Indus River, creating the largest empire in the world to that date.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] But Darius and his son Xerxes I failed to expand into Greece, with expeditions in 490 and 480 BC eventually failing.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid dynasty and empire fell to Alexander the Great by 330 BC, and after Alexander's death, much of the area previously ruled by the Cyrus and his successors was ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Parthia was an Iranian civilisation situated in the northeastern part of modern Iran.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Their power was based on a combination of military power based on heavy cavalry with a decentralised governing structure based on a federated system.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Parthian Empire was led by the Arsacid dynasty, which by around 155 BC under Mithradates I had mostly conquered the Seleucid Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Parthia had many wars with the Romans, but it was rebellions within the empire that ended it in the 3rd century AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Sasanian Empire began when the Parthian Empire ended in AD 224.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Their rulers claimed the Achaemenids as ancestors and set up their capital at Ctesiphon in Mesopotamia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Their period of greatest military expansion occurred under Shapur I, who by the time of his death in AD 272 had defeated Roman imperial armies and set up buffer states between the Sasanians and Roman Empires.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After Shapur, the Sasanians were under more pressure from the Kushans to their east as well as the Roman then Byzantine Empire to its west.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] However, the Sasanians rebuilt and founded numerous cities and their merchants travelled widely and introduced crops such as sugar, rice, and cotton into the Iranian plateau.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] But in AD 651, the last Sassanid emperor was killed by the expanding Islamic Arabs.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites first came to Anatolia about 1900 BC and during the period 1600–1500 they expanded into Mesopotamia where they adopted the cuneiform script to their Indo-European language.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By 1200 their empire stretched to Phoenicia and eastern Anatolia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] They improved two earlier technologies from Mesopotamia and spread these new techniques widely – improved iron working and light chariots with spoked wheels in warfare.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites introduced the casting of iron with molds and then hammering it which enabled weapons and tools to be made stronger and also cheaper.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Although chariots had been used previously, the use of spoked wheels allowed the chariots to be much lighter and more maneuverable.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In 1274 BC the Hittites clashed with the Egyptians at the Battle of Kadesh, where both sides claimed victory.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In 1207 BC the Hittite capital of Hattusa was sacked, ending the Hittite Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Israel and Judah were related Iron Age kingdoms of the ancient Levant and had existed during the Iron Ages and the Neo-Babylonian, Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The name Israel first appears in the stele of the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah around 1209 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This "Israel" was a cultural and probably political entity of the central highlands, well enough established to be perceived by the Egyptians as a possible challenge to their hegemony, but an ethnic group rather than an organised state.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Israel had emerged by the middle of the 9th century BC, when the Assyrian King Shalmaneser III named "Ahab the Israelite" among his enemies at the battle of Qarqar (853).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Judah emerged somewhat later than Israel, probably during the 9th century BC, but the subject is one of considerable controversy.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Israel came into conflict with the Assyrians, who conquered Israel in 722 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire did the same to Judah in 586.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After both conquests, the conquering forces deported many of the inhabitants to other regions of their respective empires.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Phoenicia was an ancient civilisation centred in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coastal regions of modern-day Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Phoenician civilisation was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean between the period of 1550 to 300 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] One Phoenician colony, Carthage, ruled an empire in the Western Mediterranean until being defeated by Rome in the Punic Wars.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Phoenicians invented the Phoenician alphabet, the forerunner of the modern alphabet still in use today.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The history of Pre-Islamic Arabia before the rise of Islam in the AD 630s is not known in great detail.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Archaeological exploration in the Arabian Peninsula has been sparse; indigenous written sources are limited to the many inscriptions and coins from southern Arabia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Existing material consists primarily of written sources from other traditions (such as Egyptians, Greeks, Persians, Romans, etc.) and oral traditions later recorded by Islamic scholars.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] A number of small kingdoms existed in Arabia from around AD 100 to perhaps about AD 400.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt was a long-lived civilisation geographically located in north-eastern Africa.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It was concentrated along the middle to lower reaches of the Nile River, reaching its greatest extent during the 2nd millennium BC, which is referred to as the New Kingdom period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It reached broadly from the Nile Delta in the north, as far south as Jebel Barkal at the Fourth Cataract of the Nile.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Extensions to the geographical range of ancient Egyptian civilisation included, at different times, areas of the southern Levant, the Eastern Desert and the Red Sea coastline, the Sinai Peninsula, and the Western Desert (focused on the several oases).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt developed over at least three and a half millennia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It began with the incipient unification of Nile Valley polities around 3100 BC, traditionally under Menes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Overseeing these activities were a socio-political and economic elite under the figure of a (semi)-divine ruler from a succession of ruling dynasties.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egyptian history is divided across various periods, beginning with the Old Kingdom, which saw pyramid building on a large scale.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After 2100 BC, the Old Kingdom dissolved into smaller states during the First Intermediate Period, which lasted about 100 years.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom began around 2000 BC with the reunification of Egypt under pharoes ruling from Thebes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom ended with the conquest of northern Egypt by the Hyksos around 1650 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Hyksos were expelled from Egypt and the land was reunited in the New Kingdom around 1550 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This period lasted until about 1000 BC, and saw Egypt expand its borders into Palestine and Syria.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Third Intermediate Period was marked by the rule of priests as well as the conquest of Egypt by Nubian kings and then later Assyria, Persia, and Macedonians.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Carthage was founded around 814 BC by Phoenician settlers.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Carthage was a city-state that ruled an empire through alliances and trade influence that stretched throughout North Africa and modern Spain.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] At the height of the city's influence, its empire included most of the western Mediterranean.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The empire was in a constant state of struggle with the Roman Republic, which led to a series of conflicts known as the Punic Wars.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After the third and final Punic War, Carthage was destroyed and then occupied by Roman forces.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Nearly all of the territory held by Carthage fell into Roman hands.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Ta-Seti kingdom in Nubia to the south of Egypt was conquered by Egyptian rulers around 3100 BC, but by 2500 BC the Nubians had created a new kingdom further south, known as the Kingdom of Kush, centred on the upper Nile with a capital at Kerma.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In the Egyptian New Kingdom period, Kush once more was conquered by Egypt.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] However, by 1100 BC a new kingdom of Kush had formed, with a capital at Napata.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Nubian rulers conquered Egypt around 760 BC and retained control for about a century.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum was an important trading nation in northeastern Africa centred in present-day Eritrea and northern Ethiopia, it existed from approximately AD 100 to 940, growing from the Iron Age proto-Aksumite period around the 4th century BC to achieve prominence by the 1st century AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum at its height by the early 6th-century AD extended through much of modern Ethiopia and across the Red Sea to Arabia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The capital city of the empire was Aksum, now in northern Ethiopia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Nok culture appeared in Nigeria around 1000 BC and mysteriously vanished around AD 200.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation's social system is thought to have been highly advanced.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Nok civilisation was considered to be the earliest sub-Saharan producer of life-sized Terracotta which have been discovered by archaeologists.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Nok also used iron smelting that may have been independently developed.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation of Djenné-Djenno was located in the Niger River Valley in the country of Mali and is considered to be among the oldest urbanised centres and the best-known archaeology site in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This archaeological site is located about 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) away from the modern town and is believed to have been involved in long-distance trade and possibly the domestication of African rice.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The site is believed to exceed 33 hectares (82 acres); however, this is yet to be confirmed with extensive survey work.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] With the help of archaeological excavations mainly by Susan and Roderick McIntosh, the site is known to have been occupied from 250 BC to AD 900.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The city is believed to have been abandoned and moved where the current city is located due to the spread of Islam and the building of the Great Mosque of Djenné.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Previously, it was assumed that advanced trade networks and complex societies did not exist in the region until the arrival of traders from Southwest Asia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] However, sites such as Djenné-Djenno disprove this, as these traditions in West Africa flourished long before.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Towns similar to that at Djenne-Jeno also developed at the site of Dia, also in Mali along the Niger River, from around 900 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Dhar Tichitt and Oualata were prominent among the early urban centres, dated to 2000 BC, in present-day Mauritania.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] About 500 stone settlements littered the region in the former savannah of the Sahara.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It has been found that the Soninke of the Mandé peoples were responsible for constructing such settlements.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Around 300 BC, the region became more desiccated and the settlements began to decline, most likely relocating to Koumbi Saleh.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] From the type of architecture and pottery, it is believed that Tichit was related to the subsequent Ghana Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Old Jenne (Djenne) began to be settled around 300 BC, producing iron and with sizeable population, evidenced in crowded cemeteries.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The inhabitants and creators of these settlements during these periods are thought to have been ancestors of the Soninke people.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Peoples speaking precursors to the modern-day Bantu languages began to spread throughout southern Africa, and by 2000 BC they were expanding past the Congo River and into the Great Lakes area.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By AD 1000 these groups had spread throughout all of southern Africa south of the equator.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Iron metallurgy and agriculture spread along with these peoples, with the cultivation of millet, oil palms, sorghum, and yams as well as the use of domesticated cattle, pigs, and sheep.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These technologies helped increase population, and settled communities became common in sub-Saharan Africa except in deserts or heavy forests.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Paleolithic tools have been discovered in India dating to 200,000 years ago, and Neolithic sites are known from near the Indus Valley dating to around 8000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Agriculture began in the Indus Valley around 7000 BC, and reached the Ganges Valley by 3000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Barley, cotton, and wheat were grown and the population had domesticated cattle, goats, and sheep.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Indus Valley Civilisation developed around 3000 BC in the Indus and Ghaggar-Hakra river valleys of north-east Afghanistan, Pakistan, and western India.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Another name for this civilisation is Harappan, after the first of its cities to be excavated, Harappa (now in the Pakistani province of Punjab).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Harappan civilisation grew out of the earlier agricultural communities as they evolved into cities.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These communities created and traded jewelry, figurines, and seals that appear widely scattered throughout Mesopotamia, Afghanistan, and Iran.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Chickens were domesticated in addition to the earlier crops and animals.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] They developed their own writing system, the Indus Valley script, which is still mostly undeciphered.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The exact structure of society and the way the cities were governed is not known.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By about 1600 BC, the Indus Valley culture had abandoned many of their cities, including Mohenjo-Daro.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The exact reason for this decline is not known.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Indo-European speaking peoples began to spread into India about 1500 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The *Rigveda*, in Sanskrit, dates to this period and begins a period often known as the Vedic period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Between 1500 and 500 BC these peoples spread throughout most of India and had begun to found small cities.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Vedic society was characterised by the *varna* system which divided society into four broad castes, which were later elaborated.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By the end of the Vedic period, this way of organising society had become central to Indian society.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Religion in the late Vedic period was evolving into Hinduism, which spread throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Siddhartha Gautama, born around 560 BC in northern India, went on to found a new religion based on his ascetic life – Buddhism.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This faith also spread throughout Eastern and Southeastern Asia after his death.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This period also saw the composition of the epics *Ramayana* and *Mahabharata*.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The kingdom of Magadha rose to prominence under a number of dynasties that peaked in power under the reign of Ashoka Maurya, one of India's most legendary and famous emperors.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] During the reign of Ashoka, the four dynasties of Chola, Chera, and Pandya were ruling in the South, while Devanampiya Tissa (250–210 BC) controlled Anuradhapura (now Sri Lanka).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These kingdoms, while not part of Ashoka's empire, were in friendly terms with the Maurya Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] An alliance existed between Devanampiya Tissa and Ashoka of India, who sent Buddhist missionaries to Sri Lanka.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Most of North India was reunited under the Gupta Empire beginning under Chandragupta I around AD 320.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Under his successors the empire spread to include much of India except for the Deccan Plateau and the very south of the peninsula.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This was a period of relative peace, and the Gupta rulers generally left administration in local rulers.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Gupta Empire was weakened and ultimately ruined by the raids of Hunas (a branch of the Hephthalites emanating from Central Asia), and the empire broke up into smaller regional kingdoms by the end of the fifth century AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] India would remain fragmented into smaller states until the rise of the Mughal Empire in the 1500s.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Neolithic period of Southeast Asia was characterised by several migrations into Mainland and Island Southeast Asia from southern China by Austronesian, Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Hmong–Mien speakers.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Territorial principalities in both Insular and Mainland Southeast Asia, characterised as "agrarian kingdoms", developed an economy by around 500 BC based on surplus crop cultivation and moderate coastal trade of domestic natural products.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Several states of the Malayan-Indonesian "thalassian" zone shared these characteristics with Indochinese polities like the Pyu city-states in the Irrawaddy River valley, the Văn Lang kingdom in the Red River Delta and Funan around the lower Mekong.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Văn Lang, founded in the 7th century BC, endured until 258 BC under the Hồng Bàng dynasty, as part of the Đông Sơn culture that sustained a dense and organised population that produced an elaborate Bronze Age industry.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Intensive wet-rice cultivation in an ideal climate enabled the farming communities to produce a regular crop surplus that was used by the ruling elite to raise, command and pay work forces for public construction and maintenance projects such as canals and fortifications.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The earliest known evidence of copper and bronze production in Southeast Asia was found at Ban Chiang in north-east Thailand and among the Phùng Nguyên culture of northern Vietnam around 2000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Đông Sơn culture established a tradition of bronze production and the manufacture of evermore refined bronze and iron objects, such as plows, axes and sickles with shaft holes, socketed arrows and spearheads and small ornamented items.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By about 500 BC, large and delicately decorated bronze drums of remarkable quality, weighing more than 70 kg (150 lb), were produced in the laborious lost-wax casting process.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This industry of highly sophisticated metal processing was developed independent of Chinese or Indian influence.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Historians relate these achievements to the presence of organised, centralised and hierarchical communities and a large population.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Between 1000 BC and 100 AD, the Sa Huỳnh culture flourished along the south-central coast of Vietnam.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ceramic jar burial sites that included grave goods have been discovered at various sites along the entire territory.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Among large, thin-walled terracotta jars, ornamented and colorized cooking pots, glass items, jade earrings and metal objects were deposited near the rivers and along the coast.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Around 3000 to 1500 BC, a large-scale migration of Austronesians, known as the Austronesian expansion began from Taiwan.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Population growth primarily fuelled this migration.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonised the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BC or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 AD, when there was another surge of island colonisation.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 AD; Hawaii by 900 AD; Rapa Nui by 1000 AD; and New Zealand by 1200 AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Austronesians established prehistoric maritime trade networks in Island Southeast Asia, including the Maritime Jade Road, a jade trade network, in Southeast Asia which existed in Taiwan and the Philippines from 2000 BC to 1000 AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The trade was established by links between the indigenous peoples of Taiwan and the Philippines, and later included parts of Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, and other areas in Southeast Asia (known as the Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Lingling-o artefacts are among the notable archaeological finds originating from the Maritime Jade Road.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] During the operation of the Maritime Jade Road, the Austronesian spice trade networks were also established by Islander Southeast Asians with Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1000 to 600 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BC, based on such archaeological evidence as banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Estimates for when this occurred vary from the 1st century AD to as late as the 6th to 7th centuries AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By around the 2nd century BC, the Neolithic Austronesian jade and spice trade networks in Southeast Asia connected with the maritime trade routes of South Asia, the Middle East, eastern Africa, and the Mediterranean, becoming what is now known as the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the 10th century, the eastern part of the route was primarily used by Southeast Asian Austronesian traders using distinctive lashed-lug ships, although Tamil and Persian traders also sailed the western parts of the routes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It allowed the exchange of goods from East and Southeast Asia on one end, all the way to Europe and eastern Africa on the other.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Srivijaya, an Austronesian polity founded at Palembang in 682 AD, rose to dominate the trade in the region around the straits of Malacca and Sunda and the South China Sea emporium by controlling the trade in luxury aromatics and Buddhist artefacts from West Asia to a thriving Tang market.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It emerged through the conquest and subjugation of neighbouring thalassocracies.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These included Melayu, Kedah, Tarumanagara, and Mataram, among others.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These polities controlled the sea lanes in Southeast Asia and exploited the spice trade of the Spice Islands, as well as maritime trade-routes between India and China.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Chinese civilisation that emerged within the Yellow River valley is one of earliest civilisations in the world.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Prior to the formation of civilisation, neolithic cultures such as the Longshan and Yangshao dating to 5000 BC produced sophisticated pottery, cultivated millet, and likely produced clothes woven from hemp and silk.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Rice was also farmed and pigs and water buffalo were kept for food.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Longshan potters may have used the pottery wheel to produce their wares.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Chinese traditions described three ancient dynasties that predated the unification under the Qin and Han dynasties.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These were the Xia, the Shang, and the Zhou.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] It was not until the later 20th century that many historians considered the Shang or Xia to be anything other than legendary.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Little is yet known about the Xia, which appears to have begun around 2200 BC, and may have controlled parts of the Yangtze River valley.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Shang dynasty traditionally is dated to 1766 to 1122 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Bronze was central to Shang culture and technology, with chariots and bronze weapons helping to expand Shang control over northern China.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The cities at Ao and Yinxu, near Anyang, have been excavated and city walls, royal palaces, and archives as well as tombs and workshops were found.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] A system of writing developed, beginning with oracle bones, of which over 100,000 are still extant.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Towards the end of the 2nd millennium BC, the Shang were overrun by the Zhou dynasty from the Wei River valley to the west.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou rulers at this time invoked the concept of the Mandate of Heaven to legitimize their rule, a concept that would be influential for almost every successive dynasty.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Zhou initially established their capital in the west near modern Xi'an, near the Yellow River, but they would preside over a series of expansions into the Yangtze River valley.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Zhou administration was decentralised, with local elites responsible for collecting tribute and providing military support to the Zhou rulers.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In the 8th century BC, power became decentralized during the Spring and Autumn period, named after the influential *Spring and Autumn Annals*.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In this period, local military leaders used by the Zhou began to assert their power and vie for hegemony.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The situation was aggravated by the invasion of other peoples, forcing the Zhou to move their capital east to Luoyang.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In each of the hundreds of states that eventually arose, local strongmen held most of the political power and continued their subservience to the Zhou kings in name only.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Hundred Schools of Thought of Chinese philosophy blossomed during this period, and such influential intellectual movements as Confucianism, Taoism, Legalism and Mohism were founded, partly in response to the changing political world.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After further political consolidation, seven prominent states remained by the end of the 5th century BC, and the years in which these few states battled each other is known as the Warring States period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Though there remained a nominal Zhou king until 256 BC, he was largely a figurehead and held little power.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] As neighboring territories of these warring states, including areas of modern Sichuan and Liaoning, were annexed by the growing power of the rulers of Qin, they were governed under the new local administrative system of commandery.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The final expansion in this period began during the reign of Ying Zheng, the king of Qin.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] His unification of the other six powers, and further annexations to the south and southeast by 213 BC enabled him to proclaim himself the First Emperor (Qin Shi Huangdi).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Qin Shi Huangdi ruled the unified China directly with absolute power.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In contrast to the decentralised and feudal rule of earlier dynasties the Qin ruled directly.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Nationwide the philosophy of legalism was enforced and publications promoting rival ideas such as Confucianism were prohibited.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In his reign unified China created the first continuous Great Wall with the use of forced labour.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Invasions were launched southward to annex Vietnam.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Qin period also saw the standardisation of the Chinese writing system and the government unified the legal systems as well as setting standardised units of measurement throughout the empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After the emperor's death rebellions began and the Han dynasty took power and ruled China for over four centuries with a brief interruption from AD 9 to 23.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Han dynasty promoted the spread of iron agricultural tools, which helped create a food surplus that led to a large growth of population during the Han period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Silk production also increased and the manufacture of paper was invented.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Though the Han enjoyed great military and economic success, it was strained by the rise of aristocrats who disobeyed the central government.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Public frustration provoked the Yellow Turban Rebellion; though a failure it nonetheless accelerated the empire's downfall.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After AD 208, the Han dynasty broke up into rival kingdoms.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] China would remain divided for almost the next 400 years.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The East Asian nations adjacent to China were all profoundly influenced by their interactions with Chinese civilisation.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Northwestern Korea and Northern Vietnam were brought under Han rule by Han Wudi in the second century BC, and this rule led to cultural influences on both areas for many centuries to come.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Wudi also faced a threat from the Xiongnu, a nomadic people from the Central Asian steppes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Wudi's invasions ended the Xiongnu state.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In 108 BC, the Han dynasty of China conquered much of northern Korea but when Han China began its decline, three kingdoms in Korea – those of Baekje, Goguryeo and Silla – emerged and expelled the Chinese.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Goguryeo and Baekje were eventually destroyed by a Tang dynasty and Silla alliance.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Silla then drove out the Tang dynasty in 676 to control most of the Korean peninsula undisputed.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Jomon culture formed in Japan before 500 BC and under Chinese influence became the Yayoi culture which built large tombs by AD 200.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In the 300s, a kingdom formed in the Yamato plain, perhaps influenced by Korean refugees.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] In pre-Columbian times, several large, centralised ancient civilisations developed in the Western Hemisphere, both in Mesoamerica and western South America.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Beyond these areas, the use of agriculture expanded to the southwest of the continental United States by 1200 BC, and into the eastern woodlands of North America by AD 100.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Andean civilisation began with the rise of organised fishing communities from 3500 BC onwards.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Along with a sophisticated maritime society came the construction of large monuments, which likely existed as community centres.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The peoples of this area grew beans, cotton, peanuts, and sweet potatoes, fished in the ocean, and by about 2000 BC had added the potato to their crops.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Chavin culture, based around the Chavin cult, emerged around 1000 BC and led to large temples and artworks as well as sophisticated textiles.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Gold, silver, and copper were worked for jewelry and occasionally for small copper tools.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After the decline of Chavin culture, a number of cities formed after about 200 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The cities at Huari, Pucara, and Tiahuanaco were all likely over 10,000 residents.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] From about AD 300, the Mochica culture arose along the Moche River.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These people left painted pottery depicting their society and culture with a wide range of varied subjects.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Besides the Mochica, there were a number of other large states in the Andes after about AD 100.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Included amongst these are the Nazca culture, who were mainly village-dwelling but left behind a large ceremonial centre at Cahuachi as well as the Nazca lines, a large number of huge designs set into the desert floor.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural cultivation began around 8000 BC in Mesoamerica, where avocados, beans, chili peppers, gourds, and squashes were grown from about 7000 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Around 4000 BC maize began to be grown, and soon after this tomatoes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Settlements appeared around 3000 BC and by 2000 BC most of Mesoamerica was practicing agriculture.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Although some animals were domesticated — notably turkeys and dogs — the lack of suitable large animals precluded the development of animals used for transportation or labour.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Around 1200 BC the first Olmec centre of San Lorenzo was founded, which remained the centre of Olmec civilisation until around 800 BC when La Venta took over before losing primacy to Tres Zapotes around 400 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These and other Olmec centres were groups of tombs, temples, and other ceremonial sites built of stone.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Their construction testifies to the complexity of Olmec society, although the exact nature of how they were governed is not known.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] They also erected large stone sculptures of human heads and other subjects.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Jade jewelry and other Olmec objects are found throughout Mesoamerica, likely having travelled via trade networks.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Olmec writing system was mainly used for recording their calendar, both of which influenced later Mesoamerican cultures.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After the decline of the Olmecs, other civilisations in Mesoamerica either arose or emerged from the Olmec shadow - the Mayans, the Zapotecs, and Teotihuacan.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Zapotecs began around 500 BC in the Oaxaca Valley at the site of Monte Alban.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Monte Alban grew to around 25,000 residents in the period around AD 200, with the city having large stone temples and an expansive stone plaza.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Like the Olmecs, they had a writing system and calendar.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] But by AD 900 Monte Alban was deserted for unknown reasons.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Teotihuacan developed around AD 200 and centred on the city of Teotihuacan, which grew to perhaps as many as 200,000 inhabitants at its height.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Teotihuacan lasted until around AD 700, when it was burned and vandalised.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Maya culture began to emerge around AD 300 in the Yucatan Peninsula and modern-day Guatemala.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] During the 600 years of the Classical Maya period, more than 80 Mayan sites were built, with temples, pyramids, and palaces the focal point of each centre.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The most influential was Tikal, but Mayan civilisation was based on city-states which often were at war with each other.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This seems not to have restricted trade, which went on between the cities.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] A priestly elite kept astronomical and calendrical knowledge, recording it with a writing system based on the Olmec system of glyphs.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] History, poetry, and other records were recorded in books, most of which did not survive the Spanish conquest of Mesoamerica.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Mathematics was also studied, and they used the concept of zero in their calculations.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Mayan civilisation began to decline about AD 800, and most of its cities were deserted soon afterwards.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Organized societies, in the ancient United States or Canada, were often mound builder civilisations.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] One of the most significant of these was the Poverty Point culture that existed in the U.S. state of Louisiana, and was responsible for the creation of over 100 mound sites.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Mississippi River was a core area in the development of long-distance trade and culture.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Following Poverty Point, successive complex cultures such as the Hopewell emerged in the Southeastern United States in the Early Woodland period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Before AD 500 many mound builder societies retained a hunter gatherer form of subsistence.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Greece is home to the first advanced civilizations in Europe beginning with the Cycladic culture on the islands of the Aegean Sea around 3200 BC, and the Minoan civilisation in Crete (2700–1500 BC).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Minoans built large palaces decorated with frescoes and wrote in the undeciphered script known as Linear A.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Mycenaean civilization, the first distinctively Greek civilisation later emerged on the mainland (1600–1100 BC), consisting of a network of palace-centred states and writing the earliest attested form of Greek with the Linear B script.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Mycenaeans gradually absorbed the Minoans, but collapsed violently around 1200 BC, along with several other civilizations in the eastern Mediterranean, during the regional event known as the Late Bronze Age collapse.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This ushered in a period known as the Greek Dark Ages, from which written records are absent.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Archaic Period in Greece is generally considered to have lasted from around the 8th century BC to the invasion by Xerxes in 480 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This period saw the expansion of the Greek world around the Mediterranean, with the founding of Greek city-states as far afield as Sicily in the west and the Black Sea in the east.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Politically, the Archaic period in Greece saw the collapse of the power of the old aristocracies, with democratic reforms in Athens and the development of Sparta's unique constitution.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The end of the Archaic period also saw the rise of Athens, which would come to be a dominant power in the Classical Period, after the reforms of Solon and the tyranny of Pisistratus.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Classical Greek world was dominated throughout the 5th century BC by the major powers of Athens and Sparta.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The period in Greek history from the death of Alexander the Great until the rise of the Roman empire and its conquest of Egypt in 30 BC is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] After Alexander's death, a series of wars between his successors eventually led to three large states being formed from parts of Alexander's conquests, each ruled by a dynasty founded by one of the successors.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These were the Antigonids, the Selucids, and the Ptolemies.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These three kingdoms, along with smaller kingdoms, spread Greek culture and lifestyles into Asia and Egypt.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] These varying states eventually were conquered by Rome or the Parthian Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Rome was a civilisation that grew out of the city-state of Rome, originating as a small agricultural community founded on the Italian peninsula in the 8th century BC, with influences from Greece and other Italian civilisations, such as the Etruscans.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Traditionally Rome was founded as a monarchy that then became a republic.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Rome expanded through the Italian peninsula through a series of wars in the fifth through the third centuries BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] This expansion brought the Roman republic into conflict with Carthage, leading to a series of Punic Wars, that ended with the destruction of Carthage in 146 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Rome then expanded into Greece and the eastern Mediterranean, while a series of internal conflicts led to the republic becoming an empire ruled by an emperor by the first century AD.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Throughout the first and second centuries AD, the Empire grew slightly while spreading Roman culture throughout its boundaries.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] A number of factors led to the eventual decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Roman Empire underwent considerable social, cultural and organisational change starting with reign of Diocletian, who began the custom of splitting the empire into eastern and western halves ruled by multiple emperors.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Constantine the Great initiated the process of Christianisation of the empire and established a new capital at Constantinople.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Migrations of Germanic tribes disrupted Roman rule from the late 4th century onwards, culminating in the eventual collapse of the empire in the West in 476, replaced by the so-called barbarian kingdoms.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The resultant cultural fusion of Greco-Roman, Germanic and Christian traditions formed the cultural foundations of Europe.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] There has been attempt by scholars to connect European late antiquity to other areas in Eurasia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Celts were a diverse group of tribal societies in Iron Age Europe.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Proto-Celtic culture formed in the Early Iron Age in Central Europe (Hallstatt period, named for the site in present-day Austria).
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By the later Iron Age (La Tène period), Celts had expanded over wide range of lands: as far west as Ireland and the Iberian Peninsula, as far east as Galatia (central Anatolia), and as far north as Scotland.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] By the early centuries AD, following the expansion of the Roman Empire and the Great Migrations of Germanic peoples, Celtic culture had become restricted to the British Isles.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Huns were a nomadic people who formed a large state in Eastern Europe by about AD 400, and under their leader Attila, they fought against both sections of the Roman Empire.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] However, after Attila's death, the state fell apart and the Huns' influence in history disappeared.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Hun-Xiongnu connection is controversial at best and is often disputed but is also not completely discredited.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Migration of Germanic peoples to Britain from what is now northern Germany and southern Scandinavia is attested from the 5th century.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Groups of Goths migrated into western Europe, with the Ostrogoths eventually settling in Italy before being conquered by the Lombards.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] A related people, the Visigoths, settled in Spain, founding a kingdom that lasted until it was conquered by Islamic rulers in the AD 700s.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] Several Indo-european speaking peoples inhabited the Balkan peninsula including the Thracians and Illyrians, that were divided into many tribes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The first Illyrian tribe to create its own kingdom was the Enchelei, which formed its own state around the 8th-7th century BC and reached the height of their power under king Bardylis.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p02] The Ardiani were infamous for their piracy and wars against the Roman Empire, for the first time between 229 BC-228 BC, then for a second time during 220 BC-219 BC and for a third time during 168 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The rise of civilisation corresponded with the institutional sponsorship of belief in gods, supernatural forces and the afterlife.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] During the Bronze Age, many civilisations adopted their own form of polytheism.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Usually, polytheistic Gods manifested human personalities, strengths and failings.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Early religion was often based on location, with cities or entire countries selecting a deity, that would grant them preferences and advantages over their competitors.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Worship involved the construction of representation of deities, and the granting of sacrifices.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Sacrifices could be material goods, food, or in extreme cases human sacrifice to please a deity.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] New philosophies and religions arose in both east and west, particularly about the 6th century BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Over time, a great variety of religions developed around the world, with some of the earliest major ones being Hinduism (around 2000 BC), Buddhism (5th century BC), and Jainism (6th century BC) in India, and Zoroastrianism in Persia.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Abrahamic religions trace their origin to Judaism, around 1700 BC.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] In the east, three schools of thought were to dominate Chinese thinking until the modern day.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] These were Taoism, Legalism and Confucianism.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Confucian tradition, which would attain dominance, looked for political morality not to the force of law but to the power and example of tradition.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Confucianism would later spread into the Korean peninsula and Japan.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] In the west, the Greek philosophical tradition, represented by Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle, was diffused throughout Europe and the Middle East in the 4th century BC by the conquests of Alexander the Great.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] After the Bronze and Iron Age religions formed, Christianity spread through the Roman world.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Ancient technological progress began before the recording of history, with tools, use of fire, domestication of animals, and agriculture all predating recorded history.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The use of metals and the ability to make metal alloys was foundational for later technologies to develop.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Medical knowledge, including the use of herbs to treat illnesses and wounds as well as some surgical techniques, advanced during antiquity.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] An early very important development that allowed for further advancement was writing, which allowed humans to record information for later use.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The characteristics of ancient Egyptian technology are indicated by a set of artifacts and customs that lasted for thousands of years.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Egyptians invented and used many basic machines, such as the ramp and the lever, to aid construction processes.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Egyptians also played an important role in developing Mediterranean maritime technology, including ships.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Babylonians and Egyptians were early astronomers who recorded their observations of the night sky.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] Water managing Qanats which likely emerged on the Iranian plateau and possibly also in the Arabian peninsula sometime in the early 1st millennium BC spread from there slowly west- and eastward.
[src:barquentine/ancient-history-p03] The Hindu–Arabic numeral system with the concept of zero was developed in India, while modern forms of paper were invented in China in the first century AD.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] A **bago** is a traditional boat built by the Mandar people of Sulawesi, Indonesia.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] The hull is of the pajala-type, lightly built and allowing for shallow displacement.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] The boat is long, with the mast only making up a quarter of its length.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] A bago can be readily identified as Mandarese boat by its rudderpost style.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] Smaller-sized bagos are often used as fishing boats from which fishermen cast their nets.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] The Mandar people prefer using a bago over an outrigger canoe.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] In the present, small bagos are outfitted with a leti (lete) sail/rig, but not long ago, they had canted rectangular sails (tanja rig).
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] Bigger versions of the bago, also using the pajala-type hull, are sometimes built rather deep and round but without the angle at the end of the keel.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] These boats can be found all over Mandar coast.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] A type with nade sail, created the West Sulawesian lambo.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] Another type, with leti sail and Mandar-style flat-roofed deckhouse, may be mistaken as leti leti.
[src:barquentine/bago-boat] There is not much difference between the two except in the pattern of the placement of the planks and other details that give the characteristics of each manufacturing place of the boat.
[src:barquentine/balangay] A **balangay**, or **barangay**, is a type of lashed-lug boat built by joining planks edge-to-edge using pins, dowels, and fiber lashings.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They are found throughout the Philippines and were used largely as trading ships up until the colonial era.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The oldest known balangay are the eleven **Butuan boats**, which have been carbon-dated individually from 689 to 988 CE and were recovered from several sites in Butuan, Agusan del Norte.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The Butuan boats are the single largest concentration of lashed-lug boat remains of the Austronesian boatbuilding traditions.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They are found in association with large amounts of trade goods from East Asia, Southeast Asia, and as far as Persia, indicating they traded as far as the Middle East.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Balangay were the first wooden watercraft excavated in Southeast Asia.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Balangay are celebrated annually in the Balanghai Festival of Butuan.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The term was also used by the Tagalog people to refer to the smallest discrete political units, which came to be the term used for native villages under the Spanish colonial period.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The name of the boat was usually Hispanicized in Spanish and American records as *barangayan* (plural: *barangayanes*) to distinguish them from the political unit.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Among the Ibanag people of Northern Luzon, balangay were known as *barangay*, a term sometimes extended to the crew.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Large vessels were called **biray** or **biwong**.
[src:barquentine/balangay] In the Visayas and Mindanao, there are multiple names for balangay-type boats, including **baloto** (not to be confused with the *balutu*), **baroto**, **biray**, **lapid**, **tilimbao** (or **tinimbao**).
[src:barquentine/balangay] Cargo-carrying versions of balangay with high sides and no outriggers (which necessitated the use of long oars instead of paddles) were also known as **bidok**, **birok**, or **biroko** (also spelled *biroco*) in the Visayas.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The **karakoa**, a large Visayan warship, was also a type of balangay.
[src:barquentine/balangay] "Balangay" is a general term and thus applies to several different types of traditional boats in various ethnic groups in the Philippines.
[src:barquentine/balangay] In common usage, it refers primarily to the balangay of the Visayas and Mindanao islands, which were primarily inter-island trading ships, cargo transports, and warships.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Large balangay (especially warships), including the Butuan boats, are commonly equipped with large double-outriggers which support paddling and fighting platforms, in which case, they can be generically referred to as *paraw* or *tilimbao* (also *tinimbao*, from *timbao*, "outrigger").
[src:barquentine/balangay] Balangay warships, along with the larger karakoa, were regularly used for raiding (*mangayaw*) by Visayan warriors.
[src:barquentine/balangay] It is believed that they may have been the "*Pi-sho-ye*" raiders described as regularly attacking Chinese settlements on the coast of Fujian in the 12th century AD.
[src:barquentine/balangay] In Tagalog regions, the balangay or barangay has the same functions as in the southern islands but differ in that it is constructed through the sewn-plank technique, rather than through dowels.
[src:barquentine/balangay] In the province of Cagayan in Northern Luzon, the balangay of the Ibanag people were predominantly used within the Cagayan River system, but were also sometimes used as coastal trade ships, reaching as far as the Ilocos Region.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They were mainly used as cargo and fishing ships and differed from other balangay in being much smaller with a shallower draft.
[src:barquentine/balangay] During the 18th to 19th centuries, balangay were also often used as warships for defending coastal villages from Moro and Dutch raiders during the Moro Wars, in conjunction with watchtowers (*castillo*, *baluarte*, or *bantáy*) and other fortifications.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The raiders were regularly attacking coastal settlements in Spanish-controlled areas and carrying off inhabitants to be sold as slaves in markets as far as Batavia and the Sultanate of Gowa.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Defense fleets of balangay and *vinta* (known as the *Marina Sutil*, "Light Navy" or "Defense Navy") were first organized under Governor-General José Basco y Vargas in 1778.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They were lightly armed but fast, which made them ideal for responding quickly to raider sightings and attacks.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Notable leaders of these defense squadrons include *Don* Pedro Estevan, a *principalía* of Tabaco, Albay; and Julián Bermejo, an Augustinian friar who commanded ten balangay and established an alarm system using a line of small relay forts in southern Cebu.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They were responsible for several major naval victories against Moro raiders from the late 18th to the early 19th centuries.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The most significant was the Battle of Tabogon Bay (modern Tabgon, Caramoan) in 1818, where the combined fleets of Estevan and *Don* José Blanco defeated around forty Moro warships led by Prince Nune, the son of a sultan from Mindanao.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Nune escaped, but hundreds of Moro raiders died in the skirmish and around a thousand more were stranded and hunted down in the mountains of Caramoan.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The 1818 victory led to increased usage of defense fleets and the reduction of Moro raids to only sporadic attacks on isolated fishermen or smaller villages until their eventual suppression in 1896.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Balangay were basically lashed-lug plank boats put together by joining the carved out planks edge-to-edge.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The prow and stern posts were also composed of V-shaped ("winged") single carved pieces of wood.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The strakes were made from heartwood taken from the section in between the softer sapwood and the pith of trees.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Tree species favored include *doongon* (*Heritiera littoralis*), *lawaan* (*Shorea* spp.), *tugas* (*Vitex parviflora*), and *barayong* (*Afzelia rhomboidea*), among others.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The trees were traditionally cut on a moonlit night in accordance with local folk beliefs.
[src:barquentine/balangay] A single tree usually produces two lengths of curving planks.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Traditionally, the planks and other ship parts were shaped with straight (*dalag*) or curved (*bintong*) adzes hammered with a mallet called a *pakang*.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The master shipwright is called a *pandáy* (similar to other craftsmen in Philippine cultures).
[src:barquentine/balangay] Like most Austronesian ships (and in contrast to western ships), the keel is basically a dugout canoe (a *bangka*) made from a single log.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The keel is also known as a *baroto* which is the origin of one of the alternative names for balangay in the Visayas.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The Butuan balangay boats differ from later balangay designs in that they do not have a true keel.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Instead, they have a central plank fitted with three parallel lines of thin lugs which serve as additional attachment points for lashings.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The outer shell of the hull is built first by fitting strakes on each side of the keel edge-to-edge (to a total of six or more).
[src:barquentine/balangay] The shaping of these strakes into the appropriate curvature (*lubag*) requires a skilled *pandáy*.
[src:barquentine/balangay] They are locked in place with wooden dowels or pins (treenails) around 19 cm (7.5 in) long slotted into holes drilled into the edges of the strakes.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Some sections may necessitate the use of two or more planks for each strake.
[src:barquentine/balangay] These are attached end-to-end using hooked scarf joints.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Once the hull is assembled, it is left to season for a month or two.
[src:barquentine/balangay] After the wood is seasoned, the hull is taken apart once again and checked.
[src:barquentine/balangay] It is then reassembled in a stage known as *sugi* ("matching").
[src:barquentine/balangay] This involves fitting the strakes back together.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Once fitted, the space between the strakes is run through with a spoon-like implement called a *lokob*.
[src:barquentine/balangay] This creates a space with an even thickness in between the two strakes.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The space is then filled with fine palm fibers called *baruk* or *barok* and caulked with resin-based pastes.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The dowels are also further secured by drilling holes into them through the planks with the help of marks inscribed beforehand.
[src:barquentine/balangay] Counter pegs called *pamuta* are then hammered into these holes.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The second stage is known as *os-os* or *us-us*, which involves lashing the planks very tightly to wooden ribs (*agar*) with fiber or rattan ropes.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The ropes are tied to holes bored diagonally into lugs (*tambuko*), which are rectangular or rounded protrusions on the inner surface of the planks.
[src:barquentine/balangay] The *tambuko* occur at even distances corresponding to six dowel hole groupings.
